1. e4 e5 {In true Classical style.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {Book.} 3. Bc4 Bc5 {Lange plants his own Bishop on B4 in response to Kohtz's Giuoco Piano.} 4. O-O d6 {Lange elects to solidify his KP rather than develop a 3rd piece.} 5. c3 Nf6 {Kohtz prepares for P-Q4 as Lange clears the way for castling.} 6. b4 Bb6 {Lange is forced to retreat his Bishop.} 7. d4 exd4 {Electing to exchange and leave White with a stronger Pawn center.} 8. cxd4 Bg4 {Lange plays aggressively, developing with a pin.} 9. Bb2 O-O {Both men have secured their Kings, but Lange has a slight lead in development.} 10. b5 Ne7 {Lange aims to bring this Knight to the K-side. The alternative was 10... N-N1 with ... N-Q2 intended.} 11. Nc3 Ng6 {Lange now has both Knights and his QB aimed at White's King, with the ability to quickly mobilize additional forces.} 12. Qd2 Qd7 {Kohtz begins shifting forces to defend his K-side as Lange activates his Queen.} 13. Qe3 Rfe8 {Lange moves another big gun into position.} 14. Rad1 Nxe4 {The attack commences.} 15. Nxe4 d5 {The Pawn fork regains the piece.} 16. Be2 Rxe4 {Lange gains a tempo by attacking the Queen while recapturing.} 17. Qd2 Nf4 {The noose is starting to tighten as Lange brings yet another piece forward.} 18. Ne5 Nxe2+ {Winning a clear piece.} 19. Kh1 Rxe5 {Kohtz resigns, as 20 PxR would open a deadly diagonal for Lange's KB. } 